{
  "card_id": "support_and_resistance",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Support and Resistance",
  "aliases": [
    "Key Levels",
    "key levels",
    "Resistance Level",
    "resistance zone",
    "Resistance Zone",
    "S&R",
    "s&r",
    "s/r",
    "S/R",
    "Support Level",
    "Support Zone"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Support and resistance are key price levels or zones where price has historically reversed or stalled. In ICT, they are time-based levels (midnight open, 8:30 EST) defining premium/discount zones. In SMC, they are horizontal zones formed by clusters of pivot highs/lows, confirmed by multiple tests.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the midnight open (00:00 EST) and the 8:30 EST level as horizontal references on the chart.",
    "If price is above both midnight open and 8:30, treat the zone as a premium (resistance context for bearish setups).",
    "If price is below both midnight open and 8:30, treat the zone as a discount (support context for bullish setups).",
    "When price closes back through one of these levels, the level flips role and becomes support or resistance on the retest.",
    "Pair these time levels with an order block or fair value gap formed at midnight, 8:30, or 9:30 to confirm a reactive S/R zone.",
    "Identify significant swing points by using a pivot point indicator or lookback period (e.g., 20 bars) to filter out minor fluctuations, focusing on pivot highs and lows.",
    "Identify support/resistance on higher timeframes (e.g., daily, weekly) during top-down analysis to capture levels that are clear and widely respected by the market.",
    "Draw support/resistance as horizontal zones (use rectangle tool) that encompass the extremes of wicks and bodies of pivot clusters, not as exact lines. Zones should contain multiple pivot points at approximately the same price (at least two or three).",
    "Confirm a level as valid only after at least two distinct price tests with strong reactions (e.g., decisive bounces, engulfing patterns, sharp reversals). Prioritize levels with few but decisive tests over those with many weak reactions.",
    "A breakout is confirmed when price closes decisively beyond the zone, often preceded by tight consolidation; until then, the zone is considered active."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "These levels frame daily bias and locate reactions: ICT time levels define premium/discount for entries, combined with order blocks at 8:30/9:30 to anticipate New York reversals. SMC zones identify reversal areas: buy near support, sell near resistance, stops beyond zone. Confirmed breakouts signal momentum; broken levels flip roles for re-entries.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Drawing too many levels (using too minor pivot points or short lookback), cluttering the chart and obscuring key zones.",
    "Assuming more touches always make a level stronger; strong, decisive bounces are more reliable than numerous weak tests.",
    "Treating support/resistance as exact price lines or expecting reversals at the exact same level, instead of drawing zones that encompass price extremes.",
    "Analyzing only a limited price range without zooming out to higher timeframes to see major historical levels.",
    "Entering a breakout trade without waiting for a confirmed close beyond the zone, resulting in false signals.",
    "Overlooking tight price consolidation prior to a breakout, which often signals an impending large move."
  ],
